          "skip_reason": null,
          "validation_ok": true,
          "errors": [],
          "repaired": false,
          "latency_ms": 14340,
          "unit_kind": "paragraph"
        },
        "text": "To improve consumer protection, the Commission is considering adopting a draft directive or regulation to tackle unfair practices – such as manipulative interfaces, social media trading practices of influencers, addictive designs for digital products or unfair personalisation practices – and to ensure a level playing field for online traders.",
        "chunk_meta": {
          "section_id": "s3",
          "section_path": [
            "Contribution of CPME",
            "CONTENTS"
          ],
          "span": null,
          "chunk_quality": "ok",
          "chunk_word_count": 47,
          "char_len": 344
        }
      },
      {
        "para_id": "p4",
        "items": [],
        "meta": {
          "skipped": false,
          "skip_reason": null,
          "validation_ok": true,
          "errors": [],
          "repaired": false,
          "latency_ms": 5707,
          "unit_kind": "paragraph"
        },
        "text": "The main objective of the Digital Fairness Act (DFA) is to strengthen consumer protection on the internet. It should also provide an opportunity to clarify the framework applicable to businesses, in particular SMEs that are the first to be affected by the current regulatory overlap.",
        "chunk_meta": {
          "section_id": "s4",
          "section_path": [
            "Contribution of CPME",
            "OVERALL COMMENTS"
          ],
          "span": null,
          "chunk_quality": "ok",
          "chunk_word_count": 45,
          "char_len": 283
        }
      },
      {
        "para_id": "p5",
        "items": [],
        "meta": {
          "skipped": false,
          "skip_reason": null,
          "validation_ok": true,
          "errors": [],
          "repaired": false,
          "latency_ms": 6211,
          "unit_kind": "paragraph"
        },
        "text": "The adoption of the Digital Fairness Act is an opportunity to harmonise standards, fill some gaps in the current regulatory framework and reduce fragmentation within the European market, caused by divergent national approaches. This fragmentation creates legal uncertainties, additional compliance costs and creates an unattractive investment environment, especially for SMEs, which do not have sufficient means to navigate this legislative stack.",
        "chunk_meta": {
          "section_id": "s4",
          "section_path": [
            "Contribution of CPME",
            "OVERALL COMMENTS"
          ],
          "span": null,
          "chunk_quality": "ok",
          "chunk_word_count": 61,
          "char_len": 447
        }
      },
      {
        "para_id": "p6",
        "items": [
          {
            "topic": "Design Patterns",
            "topic_source": "dfa",
            "evidence_quotes": [
              {
                "quote": "outdated consumer design."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "topic": "Gaming",
            "topic_source": "dfa",
            "evidence_quotes": [
              {
                "quote": "video games."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "topic": "Influencer Marketing",
            "topic_source": "dfa",
            "evidence_quotes": [
              {
                "quote": "influence practices on social media"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "meta": {
          "skipped": false,
          "skip_reason": null,
          "validation_ok": true,
          "errors": [],
          "repaired": false,
          "latency_ms": 22227,
          "unit_kind": "paragraph"
        },
        "text": "The European Commission acknowledges in its Fitness Check that the current rules are based on outdated consumer design. The latter was previously considered to be 'rational and autonomous'. Yet, this vision has become obsolete. Consumer behaviour has been largely transformed by the emergence of AI, the development of influence practices on social media and the growing immersion in digital worlds such as video games. The European legislative framework must necessarily adapt to this development.",
        "chunk_meta": {
          "section_id": "s4",
          "section_path": [
            "Contribution of CPME",
            "OVERALL COMMENTS"
          ],
          "span": null,
          "chunk_quality": "ok",
          "chunk_word_count": 74,
          "char_len": 498
        }
      },
      {
        "para_id": "p7",
        "items": [],
        "meta": {
          "skipped": false,
          "skip_reason": null,
          "validation_ok": true,
          "errors": [],
          "repaired": false,
          "latency_ms": 7516,
          "unit_kind": "paragraph"
        },
        "text": "Today, SMEs face a multiplication of standards, unclear legal definitions and legal uncertainty. In view of these findings, the tax ruling must lay down clear rules, avoid overlaps with existing texts, such as the Digital Services Act (DSA), the Digital Markets Act (DMA), the Audiovisual Media Services Directive (AVMS), the Unfair Commercial Practices Directive and the AI Regulation, and ensure harmonised application in the Member States.",
        "chunk_meta": {
          "section_id": "s4",
          "section_path": [
            "Contribution of CPME",
            "OVERALL COMMENTS"
          ],
          "span": null,
          "chunk_quality": "ok",
          "chunk_word_count": 66,
          "char_len": 442
        }
      },
      {
        "para_id": "p8",
        "items": [],
        "meta": {
          "skipped": false,
          "skip_reason": null,
          "validation_ok": true,
          "errors": [],
          "repaired": false,
          "latency_ms": 6683,
          "unit_kind": "paragraph"
        },
        "text": "On the other hand, the Unfair Commercial Practices (UTP) Directive takes a principled approach that should be retained. According to the logic of this basic approach, a commercial practice is not unfair in nature. Unfairness is a matter of how the trader implements it. Unfairness is thus characterised in the context of controls which are carried out on a case-by-case basis. The only exception to the principal approach is an exhaustive list of practices considered unfair in all circumstances, annexed to the Directive.",
        "chunk_meta": {
          "section_id": "s4",
          "section_path": [
            "Contribution of CPME",
            "OVERALL COMMENTS"
          ],
          "span": null,
          "chunk_quality": "ok",
          "chunk_word_count": 84,
          "char_len": 522
        }
      },
      {
